Add two new tRPC procedures that the front-end review feature depends on.

PROCEDURE 1 — item.getAtRiskItems (src/server/api/routers/item.ts)
A protectedProcedure query that returns all items for the current user with status BAD, OLD, or FRESH, ordered BAD first then OLD then FRESH. Includes itemTypes with id, name, and suggested_life_span_seconds so the client can compute getDaysUntilExpiration without a second round-trip. The client-side useAtRiskReview hook does the final filter to exclude FRESH items with more than 3 days remaining (using the existing getDaysUntilExpiration utility in src/utils/expiration.ts).

  getAtRiskItems: protectedProcedure
    .query(async ({ ctx }) => {
      const userId = ctx.session.user.id;
      return ctx.db.item.findMany({
        where: { userId, status: { in: ['BAD', 'OLD', 'FRESH'] } },
        include: {
          itemTypes: {
            select: { id: true, name: true, suggested_life_span_seconds: true },
          },
        },
        orderBy: { status: 'asc' },
      });
    })

PROCEDURE 2 — user.markReviewComplete (src/server/api/routers/user.ts)
A protectedProcedure mutation with no input that writes lastReviewedAt = new Date() to the current user record. This is called by useAtRiskReviewSession when the user finishes all cards or taps 'Don't show today'. The localStorage key (broccoli:atRiskReview:lastCompletedDate) is set in parallel as a fast-path cache for the gate check so we don't need a network round-trip on every app open.

  markReviewComplete: protectedProcedure
    .mutation(async ({ ctx }) => {
      const userId = ctx.session.user.id;
      await ctx.db.user.update({
        where: { id: userId },
        data: { lastReviewedAt: new Date() },
      });
      return { success: true };
    })

DEPENDS ON: Schema issue (lastReviewedAt field must exist before this mutation can be written).
